                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d557">
                <head>No. 34.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wurts</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Bayard</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">St. Petersburg</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-09-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 3, 1887</date>. (Received September
                        17.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 139.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your instruction No. 99, of the 19th of last month, relating to the measures to
                    be taken for the better protection of the seal fisheries in Behring Sea, and to
                    inform you that, in obedience to it, I have communicated the invitation of the
                    Government of the United States to that of Russia, to enter into such an
                    arrangement as will put a check to the indiscriminate destruction, by the
                    citizens of either country, of the seals in those waters.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">George W. Wurts.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
